{"sessionId": "71f2c0", "runId": "pre-fix", "hypothesisId": "H1-H5", "location": "controller/text_generation.py:62", "message": "generate_text succeeded with raw patterns payload", "data": {"raw_text": "```json\n{\n  \"hero_summary\": \"You often experience a range of emotions influenced by social interactions, personal performance, and information overload, sometimes leading to persistent thoughts or actions.\",\n  \"short_summary\": \"You tend to feel irritated or uneasy when others' actions or vague family communications disrupt you. Uncertainty about tasks or future plans can lead to anxiety or doubt. Conversely, successfully completing tasks or taking moments of quiet often brings feelings of relief or calm.\",\n  \"quick_insights\": [\n    \"Others' inconsiderate actions may often lead you to feel irritated or frustrated, and you may not always address these situations directly.\",\n    \"Ambiguous family communications or self-comparisons often result in feelings of uneasiness or doubt, which can linger.\",\n    \"Uncertainty about completed work, exams, or upcoming events frequently leads to anxiety and repetitive checking or replaying thoughts.\",\n    \"A high volume of incoming information or multiple tasks often makes you feel overwhelmed and challenged to prioritize.\",\n    \"Successfully completing tasks, especially after prior worry or delay, tends to bring you relief.\",\n    \"Intentional moments of quiet or discovering new ideas often lead to feelings of calm or curiosity.\"\n  ],\n  \"detailed_summary\": \"You seem to experience emotional patterns that often relate to your interactions with others and your personal responsibilities.\\n\\nOne of the more frequent patterns suggests that when you encounter inconsiderate or disruptive actions from others, such as repeated interruptions, disorganization with shared items, or general slowness in public spaces, you may often feel irritated or frustrated (observed in at least 16 logs). These situations, for example, waiting for gym equipment (Log 28, 45) or dealing with a difficult customer (Log 11), frequently involve you not directly addressing the issue but rather experiencing the feeling lingering afterward. Similarly, interactions with family, like your sister interrupting your work (Log 8, 61) or your mom multitasking during calls (Log 42, 82), can lead to frustration when you feel unheard or disrupted.\\n\\nAnother notable pattern involves feelings of uneasiness or doubt, appearing in at least 15 logs. This often arises when you compare yourself to peers, such as looking at others' resumes or presentations (Log 14, 35, 53), leading you to feel like you are 'behind' or 'less solid.' Additionally, interactions with family members that involve ambiguous questions about your future plans (Log 36, 84) or indirect comments (Log 46), as well as perceived distance in communication (Log 29, 55), often leave you feeling uneasy, with the thoughts tending to linger even if the intensity is moderate.\\n\\nYou also tend to experience anxiety when faced with uncertainty about your work or academic performance, or when preparing for events (observed in at least 9 logs). This pattern often involves a tendency to repeatedly check things (Log 7, 43, 50, 81) or replay scenarios in your mind, such as wondering if you missed something in a submission (Log 7, 74) or answered an exam question correctly (Log 60). These moments of anxiety are often associated with an average sleep quality and a moderate intensity (level 3 or 4).\\n\\nWhen you are faced with a high volume of incoming information or multiple tasks simultaneously, you may tend to feel overwhelmed (observed in at least 8 logs). This can manifest as receiving many messages at once (Log 20, 58, 79), seeing a full schedule (Log 10), or trying to multitask during studying (Log 69). In these situations, you might find it challenging to prioritize, leading to difficulty responding or making progress immediately.\\n\\nIn contrast, positive emotional patterns also appear. You tend to feel relieved when you successfully complete tasks, particularly after periods of delay or uncertainty (observed in at least 7 logs). Examples include sending a long-delayed email (Log 12), finishing a presentation smoothly (Log 27, 56), or finding a misplaced item you worried about (Log 47). These moments are typically associated with good sleep quality and a lower intensity (level 2).\\n\\nOther positive experiences include feelings of calm, which you often find during intentional moments of quiet or unstructured time, like walking without headphones (Log 9) or sitting in a caf\u00e9 without specific tasks (Log 34). Similarly, you tend to feel curious when you encounter new ideas or potential opportunities, such as overhearing conversations about different specializations (Log 24) or exploring new career paths (Log 62). Feelings of happiness are also noted following successful physical achievements, like a strong run (Log 40), or after completing a task efficiently (Log 80).\"\n}\n```"}, "timestamp": 1775676274068}
