{"sessionId": "71f2c0", "runId": "pre-fix", "hypothesisId": "H1-H5", "location": "controller/text_generation.py:62", "message": "generate_text succeeded with raw patterns payload", "data": {"raw_text": "```json\n{\n  \"hero_summary\": \"You tend to experience a range of emotions, from frustration with external disruptions to relief after completing tasks, and often grapple with uncertainty about your performance or future plans.\",\n  \"short_summary\": \"Your emotional patterns frequently involve frustration when others disrupt your focus or expectations, and anxiety related to your own work and future. Conversely, you often find relief in task completion and calm in unstructured moments or when exploring new ideas. Overwhelm is also a common response to multiple demands.\",\n  \"quick_insights\": [\n    \"Others' actions often lead to frustration if you don't speak up.\",\n    \"Uncertainty about your work often causes anxiety and re-checking.\",\n    \"Multiple demands at once can easily make you feel overwhelmed.\",\n    \"Completing tasks, especially those delayed or with perceived risk, often brings relief.\",\n    \"Conversations about your future plans can make you feel uneasy.\",\n    \"Unstructured time and exploring new ideas tend to be calming or interesting.\"\n  ],\n  \"detailed_summary\": \"You seem to experience emotional patterns across several key areas, often related to external interactions, personal performance, and future considerations.\\n\\nOne strong pattern you tend to show is **frustration or irritation stemming from others' actions** that cause inconvenience or disruption. This pattern appeared at least 13 times. For example, you may feel irritated when waiting for someone to finish using gym equipment (Logs 28, 45) or frustrated when your sister doesn't put borrowed items back (Log 32). These feelings also seem to arise when conversations are disjointed, such as when your sister dismisses what you're saying (Log 51) or your mom multitasks during a call (Logs 42, 82). A common thread in these situations is that you often do not address the issue directly, with follow-up questions suggesting reasons like 'didn't want to deal with it' or 'didn't feel worth it,' which can lead to the frustration lingering.\\n\\nAnother significant pattern involves **anxiety, doubt, or tension related to the completeness or correctness of your own work, preparation, or decisions**, appearing at least 9 times. This can manifest as feeling like you're missing something important during exam prep (Log 26), uncertainty about an upcoming interview (Log 33), or replaying details after an exam or submission because you can't verify them (Logs 60, 74). This feeling of needing to re-check 'just in case' is also present when boarding travel (Logs 50, 81). The intensity of this anxiety can sometimes be high, as seen in a log where you were 'anxious' about submitting an assignment (Log 7, intensity 10).\\n\\nWhen faced with **multiple incoming messages, tasks, or information simultaneously, you frequently feel overwhelmed**, a pattern that emerged at least 8 times. This is evident when your inbox fills with messages from school, work, and family (Logs 20, 58, 79), or when you have several responsibilities pulling at you, like packing and finishing assignments (Logs 30, 48). In these situations, you tend to find it hard to respond or know where to start, often switching between tasks without completing them, and follow-up questions often suggest that prioritizing could be helpful.\\n\\nConversely, you often experience a sense of **relief after successfully completing tasks**, especially those with initial apprehension, perceived risks, or delays. This pattern appeared at least 7 times. Examples include feeling relieved after sending a delayed email (Log 12), finishing a presentation smoothly (Logs 27, 56), or finding a misplaced item you thought was lost (Log 47). These moments are often described as feeling 'better,' 'relaxed,' or 'controlled,' contrasting with periods of uncertainty.\\n\\n**Conversations or thoughts about your future plans, particularly when your dad asks questions**, can lead to feelings of uneasiness or tension. This pattern appeared at least 4 times, such as when you don't have a clear answer about long-term plans (Log 36) or when specific progress is hard to articulate (Log 71). You may feel 'put on the spot' or find these thoughts lingering.\\n\\nSimilarly, you tend to feel **uneasy or slightly off when receiving brief, rushed, or indirect communication from your parents**, a pattern observed at least 4 times. This can be a short call where your mom sounds rushed (Log 29), a brief text (Log 55), or a vague comment from your dad (Log 46), often leaving you with lingering thoughts or a feeling of distance.\\n\\nOn the more positive side, **engaging in unstructured downtime or exploring novel ideas tends to bring about feelings of calm or curiosity**, with 8 instances across these related themes. You may find calm in simple actions like walking without headphones (Log 9), sitting in a cafe (Log 34), or just observing surroundings during travel (Log 52). You also tend to feel curious and engaged when you overhear or discover new ideas, such as different specializations, study abroad opportunities (Logs 24, 44), or career paths (Logs 62, 83), which often make you pause and consider looking into them further.\\n\\nFinally, **comparing your progress or work to others often results in feelings of doubt or inadequacy**, appearing at least 3 times. This can happen when comparing your class progress (Log 35), presentation slides (Log 53), or resumes (Log 14), leading you to feel 'behind' or 'less polished' even if you know the comparison might not be fully accurate.\\n\\nAnother positive pattern observed is that **successful, controlled performance in physical activity or specific tasks tends to result in feelings of happiness or satisfaction**, appearing at least 4 times. This includes feeling stronger after a run or gym session (Logs 40, 59) or achieving successful outcomes in work tasks, like completing something earlier than planned (Log 80) or leading a discussion effectively (Log 17).\"\n}\n```"}, "timestamp": 1775773982674}
