{"sessionId": "71f2c0", "runId": "pre-fix", "hypothesisId": "H1-H5", "location": "controller/text_generation.py:62", "message": "generate_text succeeded with raw patterns payload", "data": {"raw_text": "```json\n{\n  \"hero_summary\": \"You've recently experienced a mix of feeling overwhelmed by multiple demands and uneasy about future planning, alongside moments of curiosity for new ideas and satisfaction from successfully completing tasks.\",\n  \"short_summary\": \"You frequently experience feelings of uncertainty or apprehension, particularly concerning academic/professional performance and future plans. External disruptions and inconsiderate actions often lead to irritation or frustration, which you tend to internalize. When faced with multiple demands, you may feel overwhelmed, but successfully completing tasks or engaging in quiet, focused activities often brings a sense of relief or calm.\",\n  \"quick_insights\": [\n    \"You often feel uncertain about tasks, performance, or future plans.\",\n    \"External disruptions commonly lead to frustration you tend not to voice.\",\n    \"Multiple demands often make you feel overwhelmed.\",\n    \"Successfully completing tasks tends to bring relief.\",\n    \"Undistracted moments can foster calm and happiness.\"\n  ],\n  \"detailed_summary\": \"You often experience feelings of uncertainty and apprehension. This frequently occurs when considering academic or professional performance, such as preparing for exams or interviews, reviewing assignments, or after submitting work. You may feel like you're missing something important or question if you've prepared enough, sometimes leading you to repeatedly check or replay thoughts about what you've done. These moments can feel quite intense, as seen when anticipating a submission.\\n\\nA related pattern involves feelings of uneasiness or tension when discussing future plans or progress, especially with family members. You may feel put on the spot when asked detailed questions you don't have clear answers for, or you might interpret indirect comments as veiled criticism. You tend to internalize these feelings, often without directly seeking clarification or expressing your thoughts, such as when your mom's brief messages leave you feeling distant.\\n\\nAnother recurring pattern is experiencing irritation or frustration due to external disruptions or perceived inconsideration from others. This can be triggered by situations like difficult customers, messy spaces left by family, people interrupting your work, or noisy environments. You tend to feel annoyed when others are inefficient or disregard boundaries, but you often choose not to address these issues directly, which can cause the frustration to linger.\\n\\nWhen faced with multiple simultaneous inputs or tasks, such as numerous notifications, overlapping responsibilities, or extensive research, you tend to feel overwhelmed. This can make it difficult to prioritize or even start tasks, leading you to switch between things without finishing them or temporarily stop making progress altogether. Some of these situations, like managing overlapping responsibilities or many incoming messages, can be particularly high in intensity for you.\\n\\nIn contrast to these challenging patterns, you also experience distinct stabilizing emotional responses. You often feel a sense of relief and satisfaction after successfully completing tasks, especially those you had delayed or worried about, such as sending a long-pending email or giving a presentation that goes smoothly. Similarly, engaging in physical activity, like a strong run or a good gym session, or taking moments for quiet, undistracted reflection, like walking without headphones or sitting calmly, tends to bring feelings of happiness, focus, or calm. Additionally, encountering new ideas or possibilities, whether in career paths or projects, consistently sparks your curiosity and interest.\"\n}\n```"}, "timestamp": 1775774930612}
