{"sessionId": "71f2c0", "runId": "pre-fix", "hypothesisId": "H1-H5", "location": "controller/text_generation.py:62", "message": "generate_text succeeded with raw patterns payload", "data": {"raw_text": "```json\n{\n  \"hero_summary\": \"Your most recent logs appear to show a mix of feeling overwhelmed by multiple demands and uneasy about future uncertainties, while also experiencing happiness from task completion and curiosity about new possibilities.\",\n  \"short_summary\": \"You tend to experience anxiety and doubt related to your performance and self-assessment, and often feel irritated or frustrated by others' inconsiderate actions without directly addressing them. When faced with multiple demands, you may feel overwhelmed, but you also tend to find relief and happiness in successfully completing tasks.\",\n  \"quick_insights\": [\n    \"You frequently ruminate on potential errors or perceived inadequacy.\",\n    \"Inconsiderate actions from others often lead to internalized frustration.\",\n    \"Multiple demands, especially from school, work, and family, can make you feel overwhelmed.\",\n    \"Successfully completing tasks tends to bring you relief and happiness.\",\n    \"Vague or questioning communication from family members can sometimes cause unease.\"\n  ],\n  \"detailed_summary\": \"You often experience irritation or frustration when other people's actions cause disruption or inconvenience, such as interrupting your focus, not listening, not following through on commitments, or being inconsiderate in shared spaces. For example, you have noted feeling frustrated by a customer changing their mind or your sister not returning items, and irritated by people using gym equipment inefficiently or asking repetitive questions in class. A common response in these situations seems to be internalizing the annoyance rather than directly addressing the issue, with you mentioning reasons like 'didn't want to deal with it' or 'didn't feel worth it' (15 instances).\\n\\nYou tend to feel anxious when you complete tasks, engage in self-assessment, or encounter situations involving potential mistakes. This often manifests as rumination about potential errors, missing details, or replaying past interactions. For instance, you might feel anxious about exam preparation, assignment ambiguity, or whether you said something wrong in a conversation. This can sometimes lead to repeated checking, like with tickets or submissions, even when verification might not be possible or necessary. One log also indicates this anxiety can reach a high intensity (10) and be associated with poor sleep quality (10 instances).\\n\\nSeparately, you may experience doubt when comparing your work or progress to others, leading to feelings of being 'behind' or 'less solid,' even if you meet requirements. You noted this when comparing class progress, presentation slides, or resumes, where yours felt 'less put together' (4 instances).\\n\\nYou may also tend to feel uneasy or tense when family members, particularly your dad or mom, make indirect comments, ask questions about your future plans or progress that you can't clearly answer, or communicate in a way that feels distant or rushed. You have described feeling uneasy when your dad asks about long-term plans or progress, or when your mom seems rushed or distant in communication. This often leads to internal rumination on the interaction rather than seeking clarification in the moment (11 instances).\\n\\nOn a more positive note, you often experience relief or happiness after successfully completing tasks, especially those you might have delayed or felt uncertain about, or when situations resolve more smoothly than anticipated. For example, sending a delayed email, finishing a presentation, finding a misplaced ID, or submitting something before a deadline have all brought feelings of relief. Engaging in positive physical activity, such as a strong run or gym session, also seems to contribute to feelings of happiness, strength, and control (12 instances).\\n\\nWhen you face multiple incoming tasks, messages, or responsibilities concurrently, particularly from school, work, and family, you tend to feel overwhelmed. This often makes it difficult to prioritize or focus on one thing, leading to delays in responding or starting tasks. You have described this with mixed inboxes, preparing for a trip, or multitasking while studying, sometimes with high intensity and poor sleep quality (8 instances).\\n\\nYou tend to feel calm when you engage in undistracted, less structured activities, such as walking without headphones, observing your surroundings from a caf\u00e9 or bus, or organizing tasks without rushing. These moments may create a sense of slowing down and reduced mental noise (4 instances).\\n\\nAdditionally, you tend to feel curious when you encounter new ideas or possibilities related to education or career paths. This can be sparked by overhearing conversations or browsing online, which may lead you to consider exploring these topics further (4 instances).\\n\\nFinally, you might feel conflicted when faced with social decisions or interactions that involve potential complications, trade-offs with other responsibilities, or uncertainty about your own motivations for engaging (3 instances).\"\n}\n```"}, "timestamp": 1775916844302}
